DataElement.preferredName: Laboratory Procedure Neuron-Specific Enolase Tumor Marker Result Upper Limit of Normal Value
DataElement.preferredDefinition: The numerical quantity established as the institutional top limit for the measured laboratory value, in mcg per liter, for Neuron-Specific Enolase, an enzyme (also known as phosphopyruvate hydratase) located in the cell membranes of neurons and can act as a tumor marker. A high level of NSE is associated with tumors of neuroendocrine origin.

ObjectClass.preferredDefinition: A procedure for critical evaluation; a means of determining the presence, quality, or truth of something.

Concepts.definition: Any procedure that involves testing or manipulating a sample of blood, urine, or other body substance in a laboratory setting.

Property.preferredDefinition: No Value Exists:A substance sometimes found in an increased amount in the blood, other body fluids, or tissues and which may mean that a certain type of cancer is in the body. Examples of tumor markers include CA 125 (ovarian cancer), CA 15-3 (breast cancer), CEA (ovarian, lung, breast, pancreas, and gastrointestinal tract cancers), and PSA (prostate cancer). Also called biomarker.:Outcome; a phenomenon that follows and is caused by some previous phenomenon.

Concepts.definition: A substance present in or produced by a tumor or by the host, that can be used for differentiating neoplastic from normal tissue based on measurements in body fluids, secretions, cells, and/or tissues. Markers are used in diagnosis, staging and prognosis of cancer, provide an estimation of tumor burden, and serve for monitoring effects of therapy, detecting recurrence, localization of tumors, and screening in general populations.
